english:
  title: A Memorial to King Gongmin
  author: Yun Sojong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven brought forth the people, yet cannot ensure each finds their place. Thus it must appoint a sage to be ruler, governing in Heaven's stead. Therefore the throne is called the Heavenly Seat, and the people are called the Heavenly People. When offices are established and duties divided, this represents the Heavenly Work itself. In our realm's system, the Secretariat holds five positions—Minister, Attendant Lord, Coordinator, Counselor, and Palace Supervisor—mirroring Heaven's Five Stars. The Military Commission represents the Northern Dipper. Among all officials, none escape this pattern; even minor clerks correspond to the celestial array. Thus titles and ranks are not the ruler's private possessions, but Heaven's own, which the ruler merely administers. A ruler cannot treat these as personal property to dispense carelessly, nor can ministers ungrudgingly assume them without measuring their talent and virtue.

    Since ancient times, sage kings divided the empire's people into four classes: scholars, farmers, artisans, and merchants. Farmers, artisans, and merchants each inherited their professions to serve above. Scholars alone had no fixed trade; they entered schools, studied classics, cultivated themselves, ordered their households, and learned the ways of serving the sovereign and governing the people. Only then were they appointed. Thus dukes and ministers fulfilled their duties, and the ruler governing Heaven's politics succeeded. Confucius said: "Titles and ranks are what the ruler administers. They cannot be lent to others. When government fails, the state follows it into ruin." Once titles become light and trivial, the court loses dignity and the royal house diminishes. When the royal house diminishes, petty men grow bold in disrespect, the people's resolve wavers, distinction between high and low vanishes, and the state faces peril.

    Our ancestors appointed none without talent to office, none unworthy to rank. The guilty were always punished; the undeserving received no reward. Thus the foolish and incompetent could not hold office, and all officials occupied their proper places.

    When Kyongnung entered the Yuan court, the eunuch Yi Taesun, favored by the Worldly Progenitor, requested a commission for his brother. Kyongnung replied: "Your brother holds the rank of captain of the guard. To leap him over to field commander violates our ancestors' law." When Taesun appealed to the Worldly Progenitor, the emperor said: "Official appointments have their laws. Your land has its ruler—why should I interfere? Let him request it himself." Such reverence for titles—none have shown since ancient times.

    Since the years of Sinchuk and Gyemyo, as state coffers depleted, office became payment for military service. Thus petty men fraudulently claimed such service; a bribe sufficed for rapid advancement. Once this door opened, it has never closed. Today merchants, craftsmen, public and private slaves all hold office. The worthy and worthless alike fill the bureaucracy. People regard court rank as dust beneath their feet, all grasping at it eagerly. So degraded has rank become that men joke: "A military commissioner sweeps beneath the ox," and "The deputy's fee—one horse." Thus has the name of office become utterly contemptible.

    When a captain rises to commissioner, to field commander, what joy remains? In peacetime this suffices. But should crisis strike, with what reward will Your Highness motivate the worthy to merit? I earnestly urge: from this time forward, grant office only to those with genuine military achievement and talent, even to your intimate companions. Let artisans and merchants settle in their trades; let no base persons soil the court. Then the people's will solidifies, high and low know their place, the court gains dignity, and the royal house commands respect.

    I have heard that Zhuge Kongming said: "The Former Han rose by cherishing worthy ministers and distancing petty men; the Later Han fell by cherishing petty men and distancing the worthy." From ancient times to now, the rise and fall of nations depends entirely upon whom the sovereign trusts. Your Highness faces chaos and calamity, yet dwells deep in the palace, sometimes neglecting governance for an entire month. You favor immature courtiers and foolish flatterers while rarely meeting ministers and elder statesmen. These flatterers know only to please and watch your countenance; their concerns are merely hawks, food, and carnal matters. Your Highness delights in their flattery and spends each day with them—does this not greatly harm your virtue?

    The palace must maintain dignity; base persons should not approach it. Yet now these flatterers move about freely, and the inner palace lacks severity. Without severity in the inner palace, how can the sovereign alone command respect? Your chief secretary, Kim Heunggyong, is unlearned—a mere blank wall—offering only "yes" and "no" with no capacity to counsel and illuminate. Yet Your Highness praises his glib tongue and servility, entrusting him to issue imperial commands and determine the rise and fall of officials. All state matters must pass through Heunggyong before reaching the throne. But one-sided hearing breeds treachery, and sole reliance breeds chaos. Who can guarantee against the crimes of Li Si and Zhao Gao?

    In the third month of this year, the sun was eclipsed. Recently, when the traitor Shin Don held power, an eclipse occurred in the seventh month—a month of darkness—yet his treachery still prevailed. Now in the third month, when yang is ascendant, one yin shadow overcomes the great sun. This is no minor portent. Surely someone deceives Your Highness; the way of the superior wanes while the way of the petty grows strong. I urge you to fear Heaven's warning, strip Heunggyong of power, expel petty flatterers from the palace, leave your deep chamber, rise with the dawn, trust no single minister. Meet daily with your prime minister, elder statesmen, and loyal men of integrity. Practice your ancestors' benevolent governance—this is the state's blessing.

    I have heard: "He who nurtures Heaven's people prospers; he who destroys them perishes." The sovereign receives Heaven's mandate to occupy Heaven's seat, and thus must accord with Heaven's will above while nurturing Heaven's people below as a parent loves an infant. Only then do the people's hearts attach and Heaven's mandate solidify.

    The Founder faced Taebong's excess and cruelty. Executing Heaven's judgment, he destroyed villains and cherished the people. Clothing merely warmed and cooled; dwellings merely sheltered from wind and rain. Deep benevolence and profound virtue nourished the masses. The successive monarchs continued this, all using frugal virtue to sustain the people. The Kyongryong Hall, the Hyosa Shrine, and the Hyonnung and Ui mausoleums—all maintained humble, unadorned construction. These are what your descendants should emulate.

    Your Highness has ruled twenty-three years in an age of calamity. The traitor Shin Don gained power, harboring evil intent, clouding your judgment, and draining the realm's vitality. He drove you to construct the Inhui Hall, extracting the marrow from the people's bones, draining their oil. Daily expenses numbered in the tens of thousands; officials exceeded tigers in cruelty; commands surpassed wind and rain in speed. Inner and outer peoples exhausted themselves in labor; the three harvests failed; the old and young starved; families could not sustain themselves. Granaries held less than a month's stores; people possessed less than ten days' provisions. The military supplies accumulated over years in the five provinces and two frontier zones were entirely exhausted in this construction, yet still insufficient.

    All Three Lands cried out, directing their resentment at the traitor. For six years, floods and droughts ravaged the land; a million souls suffered as if in boiling water. Yet fearing Shin Don's power, they dared not speak, only raising their hands to Heaven in lament: "This work was begun by the traitor Shin Don and the eunuch Kwangdae's persuasion." After Shin Don's execution, the work continued, and the people cried: "Though Shin Don initiated this, truly Kwangdae desired to secure his wealth and power, so he championed it with vigor." The people's resentment toward Kwangdae surpassed even that toward the traitor.

    Since the year Gyeongnim, our realm has fought Japanese pirates to the east and Tatars to the north. In the years Byungsin and Singak, half our people died. Within three years came the Gyemyo Rebellion, with deaths doubled from Singak. From Gihae to this day—fifteen years—floods and droughts have followed without respite; corpses fill the fields. Surviving people number scarcely one in ten. The two provinces of Cholla and Kyongsang have suffered prolonged famine; this year it worsens. March brought bitter cold; April brought no rain. Barley fails to head; seed cannot enter the soil. How shall our people live?

    The people are the ruler's Heaven; food is the people's Heaven. Without food, the people perish. Without people, how can the ruler alone preserve the realm? The capital's granaries now stand empty; the borders and five provinces face famine. Should calamity like Singak or Gyemyo strike, with what shall we provision the army? The people suffer under construction and taxation; their grievances rise to Heaven, beyond swift remedy. Should urgent crisis come, who remains willing to die for Your Highness?

    Alas! The Kyongryong Hall was the Founder's secondary shrine; the Hyosa Shrine houses his sacred portrait; the Hyonnung and Ui mausoleums hold his remains. Yet their construction is but one hundredth that of the Inhui Hall and the Main Mausoleum. The world calls our East "the land of propriety and righteousness," yet the descendants' and queen's halls exceed the ancestors'. What will the world and future ages say? How can Your Highness, for one consort's sake, invite the world's derision?

    Moreover, to prepare in advance for inauspicious events violates propriety. Kwangdae, intertwining himself in affairs to secure favor, has had the audacity to construct a stone chamber beforehand. All who hear of it express anger and lamentation, calling it profoundly ominous, yet dare not speak. Now calamities multiply and the people starve. This is no time for the ruler to enjoy flowers and gardens, yet Kwangdae builds a flower garden, damaging Your Highness's virtue and scattering the people's hearts. His crime warrants death.

    I humbly urge: Rectify Kwangdae's crime through public execution; cease construction on the mausoleums and stone chamber; demolish the flower garden. Thus quell Heaven's anger and dissolve the people's resentment.
